---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHero from '../../../components/PageHero.astro';

const states = [
  { title: 'Settled and social', body: 'The state that supports connection and learning. A teen here can listen, engage, practice skills, and access reasoning. This is where therapeutic work tends to land.' },
  { title: 'Fight or flight', body: 'The body’s response to perceived threat. Heart rate can rise, muscles can tense, and clear reasoning becomes harder to reach. What looks like defiance may be a teen reacting from a body prepared for danger.' },
  { title: 'Shutdown or freeze', body: 'A deeper response to overwhelming threat. Teens in this state can look withdrawn, flat, or numb. It is sometimes mistaken for compliance or disengagement.' },
];

const practices = [
  'Sessions begin with time to settle. The group and facilitator set a tone and rhythm before skills work starts.',
  'Teens practice noticing their own state: what activation, shutdown, and steadiness each feel like in their body, and what helps them shift.',
  'Somatic work, movement, mindfulness, sensory awareness, art, and music give teens ways to work when words are not the best entry point.',
  'The pace of disclosure and processing follows the teen. We do not push before a teen is ready.',
  'The physical environment and the quality of the therapeutic relationship are part of the clinical work.',
];
---

<Base
  bodyClass="brand-page"
  title="Nervous System Regulation & Somatic Work for Teens | Joshua Tree Health"
  description="How nervous system regulation and somatic work shape our teen PHP and IOP in Apex, NC: reading a teen’s state, pacing sessions, and the conditions that help treatment take hold."
>
  <PageHero
    title="Nervous system <em>regulation.</em>"
    sub="We pay attention to a teen’s nervous-system state, because the timing and pace of a session decide whether the work can land."
    art="nature"
    primaryCta={{ label: 'Start the conversation', href: '/get-started' }}
  />

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="meaning-title">
    <div class="container-x prose" data-reveal>
      <h2 id="meaning-title">What nervous system regulation means.</h2>
      <p>The autonomic nervous system runs largely below conscious awareness, shifting the body between states of safety, threat, and shutdown. Those shifts change what a teen can do in a given moment: how well they can think, speak, listen, and learn.</p>
      <p>We use this as a working lens — a way of noticing what state a teen is in and adjusting the pace and shape of a session, paired with somatic work that helps the body settle. It is not a stand-alone treatment; it shapes how the rest of the work is delivered.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section surface-cream-deep" aria-labelledby="states-title">
    <div class="container-x">
      <div class="section-head" data-reveal>
        <p class="eyebrow">Three states</p>
        <h2 class="section-title font-display" id="states-title">The states a nervous system moves through.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="grid-3" data-reveal-group>
        {states.map((state) => (
          <article class="info-card" data-reveal-item><h3>{state.title}</h3><p>{state.body}</p></article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="why-title">
    <div class="container-x prose" data-reveal>
      <h2 id="why-title">Why this matters for teens carrying trauma.</h2>
      <p>Many of the adolescents who come to Joshua Tree, especially those carrying trauma, spend a lot of time in the activated or shut-down states above. Their nervous systems have learned to treat a wide range of situations as threatening, often for reasons that made sense earlier in their lives.</p>
      <p>When a teen is highly activated, language and reflection can become harder to access. A useful skill may be taught at the wrong moment and never become usable.</p>
      <p>We start by noticing the conditions around the teen and what helps them settle enough to stay present. Then the rest of the work has a better chance of taking hold.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section surface-cream-deep" aria-labelledby="practice-title">
    <div class="container-x">
      <div class="section-head" data-reveal>
        <p class="eyebrow">In practice</p>
        <h2 class="section-title font-display" id="practice-title">What this looks like in a session.</h2>
        <p class="section-sub">This shapes the pace of a session and the order in which the work happens.</p>
      </div>
      <ul class="checklist" data-reveal>{practices.map((practice) => <li>{practice}</li>)}</ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="clinicians-title">
    <div class="container-x prose" data-reveal>
      <h2 id="clinicians-title">For referring clinicians.</h2>
      <p>In our program, attention to nervous-system state informs session structure and pacing, co-regulation practices in group settings, the role of somatic and expressive work, and how we approach trauma history and disclosure.</p>
      <p>If you want to talk through how this works in practice, <a href="tel:+19193355053">call us at (919) 335-5053</a>. We are glad to get specific.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section surface-green" aria-labelledby="cta-title">
    <div class="container-x">
      <div class="section-head section-head--center" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="section-title font-display" id="cta-title">See where this fits in the program.</h2>
        <p class="section-sub">Nervous system regulation and somatic work run alongside DBT skills, trauma-informed practice, and family involvement.</p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="btn btn--on-dark" href="/what-we-offer/our-approach">Learn about our full approach <span class="btn__arrow">→</span></a>
          <a class="btn btn--ghost-on-dark" href="/get-started">Get started</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .cta-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 1rem; justify-content: center; margin-top: 1.6rem; }
</style>
